                      <li><strong>4 marks:</strong> Shows understanding of branching concept for bug fixes but workflow explanation incomplete</li>
                      <li><strong>2-3 marks:</strong> Basic understanding of branching benefits but lacks specific workflow for the scenario</li>
                      <li><strong>1 mark:</strong> Shows awareness of Git branching but fails to address the specific scenario requirements</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-green-700 mb-2">Sample Answer:</h4>
                    <div class="text-sm bg-white p-3 rounded border">
                      <p><strong>Branching Strategy:</strong></p>
                      <p>Git branching allows parallel development by creating separate lines of development. The team should create a "hotfix" or "bugfix" branch from the main/master branch specifically for the critical bug fix, while maintaining a separate "develop" or "feature" branch for ongoing new feature work.</p>
                      
                      <p class="mt-3"><strong>Workflow Steps:</strong></p>
                      <p>1. Create hotfix branch from main branch: git checkout -b hotfix-critical-bug</p>
                      <p>2. Developer fixes the bug and commits changes to hotfix branch</p>
                      <p>3. Test the fix thoroughly on the hotfix branch</p>
                      <p>4. Merge hotfix branch into main branch for immediate deployment</p>
                      <p>5. Merge hotfix changes into develop branch to ensure bug fix is included in future releases</p>
                      <p>6. Continue feature development on develop branch uninterrupted</p>
                      
                      <p class="mt-3"><strong>Benefits:</strong> This approach ensures the critical bug fix can be deployed quickly without including incomplete new features, while preventing disruption to ongoing development work.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </details>
